However, the most common version of Superman is likely the one that was created by writer Jerry Siegel and artist Joe Shuster in 1933. In this version, Superman is an alien from the planet Krypton who crash-lands on Earth as a baby and is raised by farmers Jonathan and Martha Kent in Smallville, Kansas.

As a young man, Superman develops his powers and becomes a champion of truth and justice, protecting the people of Earth from threats both terrestrial and extraterrestrial. In terms of his physical abilities, Superman is considered to be the strongest man on Earth, capable of lifting large objects and flying at superhuman speeds. He has also been shown to have superhuman senses such as x-ray vision and the ability to hear sounds at incredible distances. Additionally, he possesses vast knowledge and intelligence that allows him to solve complex problems quickly.

Superman has also been shown to be invulnerable to most forms of harm, though he has been known to be vulnerable to certain Kryptonite-based weapons or magic. He also has a strong moral compass and is dedicated to protecting the innocent and helping those in need.

Overall, Superman is one of the most popular superheroes in history due to his enduring appeal as a symbol of hope and justice. His powers and abilities have inspired countless stories over the years and continue to captivate audiences today.

system:
"Skrifaðu mér gæða prófunarkerfi í Cypress sem notar Docker og einnig notast við getu Cypress til að taka skjáskot og vista þau."

1. Open a terminal in the same directory as your Cypress project.
2. Install Docker:

    `curl -fsSL https://get.docker.com -o get-docker.sh`
    `chmod +x get-docker.sh`
    `./get-docker.sh`
    This will download and install Docker.
3. Build and run the app:

    `docker build -t cypress_app .`
    `docker run -p 80:80 cypress_app`
    This will build and run a Docker image based on the Cypress app and serve it on port 80 on your machine.
4. Open Cypress in your web browser and navigate to the URL of your running container:

    `http://localhost:8080/cypress/index.html`
    This will open the Cypress browser runner in your web browser and load the Cypress test runner in the container you just created.
5. Click on the Record button and record your first test:

    `cy.visit('http://localhost:8080')`
    This will open your browser and navigate to the Cypress test runner, which is running inside the Docker container you created earlier.
6. Write your first Cypress test:

    ```cypress
    describe('First test', function() {
      it('Should display a message', function() {
        cy.contains('Hello, world!')
      })
    })```
    This code snippet defines a test with a descriptive name and a single expected message, which is that the page should display "Hello, world!".
7. Run the test:

    ```cypress run```
    This runs the test in the browser runner, simulating user interactions with the web page as if you were interacting with it yourself.
8. Verify that Cypress recorded your test:

    ```cypress open tests/index.html```
    This opens up the browser runner in another tab, showing you all of your tests in a list format. Your newly created test should appear there.
9. Click on the run button for that test:

    ```cypress run tests/FirstTest.cypress```
    This runs that specific test again, allowing you to modify it and rerun it as needed throughout your project development process.
10. Congratulations, you've successfully set up a development environment for Cypress! You can now write and run more tests to ensure that your web app is functioning correctly as you add features and make changes to it over time.

Few-shot learning (FSL) er ein af lykilframtíðarstigum í tölvulærdómi og vekur mikla athygli. Í þessari grein er fókusinn á FSL vandamálinu við skilning á samræðum, sem inniheldur tvo náið tengda verkefni: ásetningu á tilgangi og fyllingu á reitum. Það hefur verið sannað að samræðuskilningur hagnist mikið á að læra samhliða báðum undirverkefnunum.
